> What do you think of introducing a trackProgress method in BackgroundTask that takes a BackgroundProgress property and Binds it to updateProgress?

So the code would somewhat like the following?
```java
Property<...> progress = new ...
task = BackgroundTask.wrap(() => { do stuff; progress.set(100) }).trackProgress(progress)
```
This can work, but you still need to handle all the thread synchronization in the trackProgress method.

Alternatively, one could pass all the update* methods to the `wrap` function:
```java
task = BackgroundTask.wrap((updateProgress, updateMessage) => { do stuff; updateProgress(100) })
```

But to be honest, I'm not sure if it's worth all the trouble. It's not much shorter/clearer than using anonymous classes:
```java
task = new BackgroundTask<V>() {
            @Override
            protected V call() throws Exception {
                do stuff;
                updateProgress(100)
            }
        };
```

